// ResponseEntity<T> is a class in the Spring Framework that represents the entire HTTP response,
providing you with complete control over all aspects of the response sent back to the client.

this is a generic type of response which can hold any type


A RESPONSEENTITY object explicitly contains three key components in http response
1) Body (T) : The actual data payload of the response.
like List<Marks>,Student
2) Status Code : The HTTP status code indicating the outcome of the request.
200 OK, 201 Created, 404 Not Found, 500 Internal Server Error.
3) Headers : Metadata about the response.
Context-Type: application/json, Cache-Control :no-cache ... other header attributes

@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<User> getUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
    Optional<User> user = userService.findById(id);
    if (user.isPresent()) {
        // Successful response: HTTP 200 OK with the User object in the body
        return ResponseEntity.ok(user.get());
    } else {
        // Error response: HTTP 404 Not Found with no body
        return ResponseEntity.notFound().build();
    }
}

/// or we are actually using this ResponseEntity<T> like this
@GetMapping("/list")
    public ResponseEntity<List<Marks>> getAllMarks() {
        List<Marks> marks = marksService.getAllMarks();
        ResponseEntity<List<Marks>> marksList=new ResponseEntity<>(marks, HttpStatus.OK);
        return marksList;
    }

// calling from the studentapi to marks api
public void getMarksFromMarksAPI()
    {
        ResponseEntity<List<Marks>> entity = restTemplate.exchange("http://localhost:8081/marks/list", HttpMethod.GET,null,new ParameterizedTypeReference<List<Marks>>() {});
        entity.getBody().stream().forEach(System.out::println);
    }
